SIMPLE: protection
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Protection
<hw>Pro*tec"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>protectio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>protection</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of protecting, or the state of being protected;
preservation from loss, injury, or annoyance; defense; shelter; <as>as,
the weak need <ex>protection</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To your <qex>protection</qex> I commend me, gods.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which protects or preserves from injury; a
defense; a shield; a refuge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let them rise up . . . and be your <qex>protection</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Deut. xxxii. 38.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A writing that protects or secures from molestation
or arrest; a pass; a safe-conduct; a passport.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . gave them <qex>protections</qex> under his hand.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Polit. Econ.)</fld> <def>A theory, or a policy, of
protecting the producers in a country from foreign competition in the
home market by the imposition of such discriminating duties on goods of
foreign production as will restrict or prevent their importation; --
opposed to <ant>free trade</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Writ of protection</b></col>. <fld>(Law)</fld>
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A writ by which the king formerly exempted a person
from arrest; -- now disused</cd>. <mark>[Eng.]</mark>
<au>Blackstone.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A judicial writ issued to a person
required to attend court, as party, juror, etc., intended to secure him
from arrest in coming, staying, and returning.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Preservation; defense; guard; shelter; refuge;
security; safety.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Protectionism</ent>⟦br⟧
